</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">July</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">her under his protection.  When the chief returned informed of this event he went directly to her new re<span class="AddHand-author">s</span>idence, dragged her out of doors by the hair and in presence of her paramour chopped off her head.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">This camp which is in a beautiful <span class="DelHand-author">site</span> Situation consists of One hundred and Twenty leather tents mostly new as white as snow and pi<span class="AddHand-author">t</span>ched with regularity in a line forming a horse&#8217;s <span class="AddHand-author">s</span>h<span class="AddHand-author">oe</span><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Each large tent had a small one adjoining as a kitchen wher<span class="AddHand-author">e</span> the women found occupation.  The spaces between the tents were filled by stages which supported their provisions.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The Language of the Indians seems not so harsh as that of the Mandanes and is a pleasant sound.  The men are Tall, stout and well made in their manners and customs they resemble the Sioux of the plains.  They keep their tents and furniture clean and neat they dress more decently than their neighbours<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  They are however hard to deal with.  They set a high value upon every thing they have and will take and return You the payment Ten times before you can obtain the object of your bargain.</p>

